Unnecessary equality checks should not be made
Comparisons of dissimilar types will always return false. The comparison and all its dependent code can simply be removed. This includes: comparing an object with null comparing an object with an unrelated primitive (E.G. a string with an int) comparing unrelated classes comparing an unrelated class and interface comparing unrelated interface types comparing an array to a non-array comparing two arrays Specifically in the case of arrays, since arrays donâ€™t override Object.equals(), calling equals on two arrays is the same as comparing their addresses. This means that array1.equals(array2) is equivalent to array1==array2. However, some developers might expect Array.equals(Object obj) to do more than a simple memory address comparison, comparing for instance the size and content of the two arrays. Instead, the == operator or Arrays.equals(array1, array2) should always be used with arrays.